Given that the hypotenuse of a right triangle is 13, and the ratio of the lengths of the two legs is 5:12, find the lengths of the two legs.

Solution:

Let the lengths of the two legs be 5x and 12x, respectively. By the Pythagorean theorem, we have

13^2 = (5x)^2 + (12x)^2

169 = 25x^2 + 144x^2

169 = 169x^2

x^2 = 1

x = 1 or x = -1

How do you get to the garden? Gäser is a plant that blooms in spring, and which, even when it is not in bloom, has many beautifully coloured flowers. Do you know how the flower changes its hues, from purple to rose, then to orange, then brown, then green? This is the way it happens, and now my head, too, has changed colour until even some of the green leaves are brown. When we return home in the evening, let’s have some supper—my stomach is growling with hunger. Let the dishes be put on the table, and when I see how they are served, I shall eat. I only wish you could have a glance, dear reader. I see that the dishes have not been arranged on the table as I wished, and that what I wished to have is missing. In a moment I shall be raging with anger. At a table like this I should like to have dishes made of beautiful, clear, hard, and transparent glass: large glasses that can hold at a single draught a bucket of wine, and other glasses so large that a man can drink a quart of wine quickly. Next to these glasses, there should be cut-glass wines which must be the finest and the clearest that can be found: the finest, the clearest. But here there are only small, cracked, and poorly made glasses.
What? you ask. Have I gone mad, dear reader? There is no cause for alarm. Perhaps you have not thought of it, but I had already made up my mind at the time of the feast in the dining-room, about which I said nothing, that I was going to the kitchen. That is why I brought no candle with me, but I was not so inconsiderate that my presence should frighten the servants, so I gave them warning through the curtain. Let us go to the kitchen. What can be done? All I can do is to write and tell what is required for meals. I cannot ask a servant what is on his or her mind, let us try to make out from the table what a man’s thoughts are. We have just now found out that the servants, even the men, are not so much interested in the things on the table as they are in the plate that was given them.
Is it so with you, dear reader? Do you still remember the time when you sat here in your room beside your desk, and you took up a pen; then you looked into the mirror, saw that your hair and coat were not in order, took your brush in hand and comb, and began to brush and to comb? And the comb went into your mouth and your hair stood on end, so that you were not able to pay attention to what you had begun to write. Was it then so with you? Do you remember those words that came between your fingers, and made you angry because you could not write them carefully? And so on with the toilet—wearing a wig in summer is a great hindrance. I often want to write something of great importance, and there stands an untidy hair before me.
I look up once to the sideboard, where glasses are standing, and I am disturbed in my work again, and now I see the toes of a woman’s slipper. I have often been in the kitchen myself after dark. Once, on a dark night, I was sitting in the kitchen, alone with a dumb servant who could neither read nor write, when a man came in through the door of the kitchen, whom I thought was someone who had found out my occupation, and who in his attempt to get into my room began to pound away on the back of my chair with knuckles of such hard bone that I was on the defensive the whole evening and had no chance for any work, for I cannot use a knife, nor sew, nor paint. We might think that such a clumsy person would never guess what I was doing, so the kitchen is not exactly the place for someone to be doing anything good or bad. What if one should write something terrible—if you could read that, you would not dare to come into the kitchen. But the servant who came yesterday and was so interested in what was written here is also a good cook—he is called the Count’s brother-in-law, but I shall not mention his name. He is also a great reader of novels and comedies, and it was to him that I gave a present last year, and said that I had been there for 24 hours. He understood that I was a writer, for when I came from the office, I had brought home a copy of a novel by a novelist I had met there. If you want to know whether a man is a good cook, just ask him about the dishes, and listen to the reply. “This is such and such a dish.” “Well, but that looks a simple thing,” and you try to get the man to tell you how he managed to cook it. Now I know that the man who cooks simple dishes is a good one. He thinks not of himself, but of getting the dishes ready in the best manner, and is not interested in which way the dishes came into the world. A well-washed dish is a work of art, but that, dear reader, is for the next essay: I now want to talk about the dishes, and show you which are right and which are wrong.
The first thing that caught my attention was a plate: with what a great deal of skill was the plate decorated! The artist must have spent a great deal of time on this. He who sees only white and red can have no idea how fine the red is with white. But I should like to say a few words about these things, and then you must tell me what my opinion is.
I want to talk first about the dishes. What is the good that comes from them? A dish should be of a certain shape, and that shape should be formed before it is made of clay and fired. The potter makes the dish after the shape has been determined by the plumber; it is then taken to the glazier, who paints on it whatever the potter has drawn. But if you have any doubts about what dishes are like, or what colour they should be, when you go out and buy some, ask the dishwasher.
The potter paints not only the dish, but also stamps it with initials of his trade-mark. This shows that the potter has made himself a master of his art. The man who can only write his name is not much of an artist, but I should say that he is more of a tricksy craftsman than an artist. If the man who painted the dish which I have in mind had but his own word for it, I would not believe it, for it looks like a woman’s leg in stockings, and the initials are not those of a potter, but of an upholsterer. These are the initials of E. KÖNIG (KÖNIG, the King), and this is a great man who, however, did not finish the dish but died young by overworking his brains, for which I can understand the potter’s initials, because he was a good potter. But I cannot understand how a tradesman who was so clever as to be able to paint a leg and knees, should be such a stupid fellow as not to be able to make a leg and a knee.
The man who painted the dishes, however, could be a real potter, for he did not need to be taught how to paint a leg from the nude model. But what was he thinking of when he painted legs on dishes? A woman is not very different from a dish, and, in my opinion, it would be very easy for a man who paints dishes, and who can therefore paint any sort of legs, to make a woman out of clay which is quite a different sort of material from clay which you can buy in the market. For my part I am willing to believe that the man from whom I took this plate of dishes did not mean to paint a dish, but a woman’s leg. But it would be a mistake to think, merely because he painted a woman’s leg on the dishes, that he painted a woman’s leg on the dishes because he did not know any better. I would not be so foolish as to take that idea; if that were the case, I would have to buy women’s legs from the dealers in Easter eggs.
But it might happen that a man who was making dishes, and knew nothing about painting, might look at a woman’s leg and want to paint it on a dish. Would that then be a good idea? The man who has painted the initials of R. BACH on it, and have shown that the red and white stripe on the dish does not come from the potter, but from the inventor R. BACH, who wanted to make a lady’s leg out of clay and painted it so. Now comes—he wanted to make a whole woman out of porcelain and paint it red and white. It might be a very fine piece of wood and a work of art, and it would then indeed look like a human being, and one would have to see whether it is a woman or a man. It might be like that with a dish; but for my part I should not do anything to it that would prevent its looking like a human being. I do not know that man who would want to make a woman out of wood—I should say, firstly, that he did not know what he was doing, and secondly, that I did not wish to know him at all. You might say that it is unlucky to tell about something that does not yet exist, but what do you know about that? Have you not thought of something and did not tell it or write it down? I never thought of anything that can be made; I thought only of things that people have made. In this way I am not afraid of telling people of something that does not exist, because it would be an invention, and it is only an invention—for how could it be anything else—if I had done it myself? And I do not want to invent anything. But if you invent something and write it down, everyone will say that you are an inventor, and you will have to be careful of what you do with your life, where you go, and what you eat. That is why I do not write here, that you should think I am so foolish as to invent something, but only so that it shall appear that I do not believe any of the things that I say, but that I only have a few good thoughts about things which are not made, nor will ever be made. For you see, that would be too much for a poor man, and it is also of no good to anyone, for how would a potter get on if I should invent something and then let everyone make a large profit from it? Then do not think that I am a bad fellow when I speak badly of that kind of dishes.
An inventor has his own stamp—the initials which we read on the dish are always his own. I should, then, also have my own stamp, if I made a large profit out of it, because I would feel that I had done something for which I should get my reward some day—that is all I have in mind. If you have such a stamp and cannot write your name on any of your work, then you ought to take pleasure in making something, and it will not be long before you will learn to write your name.
It would be a sad thing for you, dear reader, if you were not able to write your name. I wondered how such a man could have travelled so far, and yet he could not write his own name. I have never seen any one of the greatest merit who could not write. BACH can make a whole dish, and that he can make a whole dish of a different pattern. I think that I can make a whole dish that is shaped after a man, a woman, or a horse, and has the head and arms and feet, and does not look like a man, but like a dog, or horse, or cow; and I think that in this way I can put the red and white stripes on the dish. BACH on the dishes; if I have money enough to order ten thousand dishes drawn with a knife, there is nothing to fear: you will be given a receipt every time a thousand is ready, and the rest can be done afterwards without the drawings or the oven.

I do not believe in people who can do it; but I know that it is possible to paint only on a dish and not make an elephant out of a dish.
